<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870326-0007 </DOCNO><HL> )HL    What's News --Business and Finance</HL><DD> 03/26/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><TEXT>   A BROAD TRADE BILL cleared three congressional panels and now goes to the House floor. The measure is intended to force the president to take stronger and more frequent action to ease the nation's trade woes. But the bill's fate depends on how Democrats resolve a feud over aid for import-battered industries, which Reagan likely would veto.    ---   Brazil's finance minister, Dilson Funaro, appears to have lost critical support in the country, making his future uncertain. Meanwhile, the impasse on Brazil's debt is making it more likely U.S. banks will put the loans on a nonperforming basis.    ---   The securities industry urged Congress to tighten corporate takeover rules and adopt a statutory definition of insider trading. The recommendations represent Wall Street's answer to the insider-trading scandal.    ---   Conrail's initial public offering was priced at $28 a share, raising a record $1.65 billion before underwriting fees. Trading in the stock begins today, and some analysts expect it to rise above the offering price.    ---   Anheuser-Busch's No. 2 executive resigned in connection with the company's investigation into kickbacks. Sources said it's likely there will be other resignations and firings.    ---   The dollar rose against most major currencies but gained only slightly against the yen despite continued heavy intervention. Central banks, meanwhile, have altered their intervention tactics because of the rapid growth of currency markets.    ---   Carl Icahn's TWA said it sold nearly all of its 14.8% interest in USAir Group, ending a stalled bid to acquire the carrier.    ---   A minimum wage bill was introduced by two Democratic lawmakers, bringing immediate opposition from Reagan officials. The measure would raise the minimum wage to $4.65 over three years from $3.35 currently.    ---   Ford Motor has neared General Motors in executive bonuses, having set aside $167 million for 1986 compared with GM's $169 million.    ---   Dixons Group failed to win a majority stake in Cyclops, signaling a continued fight with rival bidders for the Pittsburgh-based company.    ---   KMG Main Hurdman was censured by the SEC for &quot;improper&quot; audits of two Texas concerns. The firm settled the charges without admitting or denying wrongdoing.    ---   Charles Atkins was indicted with two others in New York for an alleged tax-fraud scheme that was used by many prominent investors.    ---   Some Northwest Airlines pilots are threatening to hold a work slowdown to protest pay and seniority discrepancies within the airline.    ---   Congress is moving rapidly to transfer final authority over airline mergers to the Justice Department from the DOT. The change is being supported by both agencies.    ---   Canada will offer cash incentives to oil and gas companies to encourage exploration and development.    ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 171,340,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials 2363.49, off 5.69; transportation 949.61, off 4.12; utilities 220.06, off 1.27.    Bonds: Dow Jones 20 bonds 94.97, up 0.32.    Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 114.71, off 0.44; spot index 115.81, up 0.75. </TEXT></DOC>